

<section xml:id="sec-gensolns-initialvalues" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>General Solutions and Initial Value Problems</title>

    <figure xml:id="video-general-solutions-ivp">
        <caption>This video goes through the content of this page.</caption>
        <video youtube="u8cZ98PIR1s" width="100%" preview="default"/>
    </figure>
<p>
  We just found that one solution to <m>\frac{dP}{dt} = 3P</m> is <m>P(t) = e^{3t}</m>. In fact, all possible solutions — the <term>general solution</term> — are of the form <m>P(t) = Ce^{3t}</m>, where <m>C</m> is any real number. I encourage you to verify that this is always a solution; we will justify why it captures all solutions later when we study separable ODEs.
</p>
<p>
  This idea generalizes naturally to the family of ODEs <m>\frac{dP}{dt} = kP</m>.
</p>
 <definition xml:id="def-general-solution-population">
    <title>Solution to the Population Growth Model</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        A simple model of a population <m>P(t)</m> is that the rate of change is proportional to the population. So <m>P(t)</m> satisfies:
        <me>\frac{dP}{dt} = kP.</me>
        The <term>general solution</term> to this differential equation is:
        <me>P(t) = Ce^{kt},</me>
        where varying over any real number for <m>C</m> gives all possible solutions.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </definition>

  <p>
    Try verifying this by differentiating <m>P(t) = Ce^{kt}</m>:
  </p>

  <solution>
  <title>Verification</title>
  <p>
    By the chain rule:
    <me>\frac{dP}{dt} = k\underbrace{Ce^{kt}}_{=\, P} = kP. \checkmark</me>
  </p>
</solution>
    <p>
  So for example, to solve <m>\frac{dP}{dt} = 2P</m>, we find the general solution <m>P(t) = Ce^{2t}</m>. Each value of <m>C</m> gives a different specific solution — together they form a whole family of curves. For instance:
</p>

<md>
  <mrow>C = 2: \amp P(t) = 2e^{2t}</mrow>
  <mrow>C = -1: \amp P(t) = -e^{2t}</mrow>
  <mrow>C = 0: \amp P(t) = 0e^{2t}=0</mrow>
</md>

<p>
  Use the slider below to explore how the value of <m>C</m> affects the solution curve. 
</p>

<figure xml:id="fig-population-slider">
  <caption>Solutions <m>P(t) = Ce^{2t}</m> for varying values of <m>C</m>.</caption>
  <interactive xml:id="interactive-population-slider" iframe="interactive-population-slider.html" width="80%" aspect="3:2">
    <static>
      <p>
        An interactive graph showing the solution curve <m>P(t) = Ce^{2t}</m> with a slider to vary <m>C</m> from <m>-5</m> to <m>5</m>. As <m>C</m> increases the curve grows more steeply, and when <m>C = 0</m> the solution is the equilibrium <m>P(t) = 0</m>.
      </p>
    </static>
  </interactive>
</figure>

  <p>
   In the graph above, notice how <m>P(0)</m> changes as you vary the values for <m>C</m>. 
    With the proper <term>initial conditions</term> we obtain a <term>specific solution</term> to a differential 
    equation.  
  </p>

  <example xml:id="ex-initial-condition">
    <title>Applying an Initial Condition</title>
    <p>
      Suppose a population <m>P</m> satisfies <m>\frac{dP}{dt} = 2P</m>, and the initial population at <m>t = 0</m> is <m>P(0) = 200</m>. Find the solution <m>P(t)</m>.
    </p>
    <solution>
      <p>
        The general solution with <m>k = 2</m> is:
        <me>P(t) = Ce^{2t}.</me>
        Applying the initial condition <m>P(0) = 200</m>:
        <me>200 = Ce^{2 \cdot 0} = C \cdot 1 \implies C = 200.</me>
        So the specific solution is:
        <me>P(t) = 200e^{2t}.</me>
      </p>
    </solution>
  </example>

  

</section>
